definition.value: Compounds that contain an amide group as a key feature of their structure and which have been used as fungicides.
A phosphocholine carrying an O-(4-diazoniophenyl) substituent.
The tetraethyl ester of [[(3-hydroxypyridin-2-yl)amino]methylene]bisphosphonic acid
Any organic aromatic compound containing two phenyl (or substituted phenyl) groups attached to a single carbon or heteroatom and which has significant antifungal properties.

The monohydrate form of doxycycline. A semi-synthetic tetracycline antibiotic, it is used to inhibit bacterial protein synthesis and treat non-gonococcal urethritis and cervicitis, exacerbations of bronchitis in patients with chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), and adult periodontitis.
An alpha-amino-acid anion that is the conjugate base of N-benzoylglycine; major species at pH 7.3.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the phosphatidyl acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are both arachidonoyl.
Any fatty acid containing nitrogen as either a substituent or a replacement for a methylene carbon.
An acyl chloride consisting of benzoyl chloride having a chloro substituent in the ortho-position.
An inorganic sodium salt having silicate as the counterion.
A thiouridine in which the oxygen replaced by sulfur is that at C-2.
A deoxyketohexose comprising the open-chain form of D-glucose lacking the -OH group at the 3-position and having the keto group at the 2-position.

An analogue of a nucleoside, being an N-glycosyl compound in which the nitrogen-containing moiety is a modified nucleotide base. They are commonly used as antiviral products to prevent viral replication in infected cells.
A hydrate, which is the hemihydrate form of the (S)-(-) (more active) enantiomer of timolol.
The monohydrate form of lidocaine hydrochloride.
A lysophosphatidic acid having the unusual property of a phosphodiester moiety linked to positions sn-1 and sn1' of glycerol; and two additional fatty acids esterified to the glycerol head group.
A lysobisphosphatidic acid carrying the fatty acyl groups at positions sn-2 and sn-2' of glycerol.
A lysobisphosphatidic acid carrying the fatty acyl groups at positions sn-3 and sn-3' of glycerol.
A dicarboxylic acid monoamide which results from addition of one equivalent of 1-naphthylamine to phthalic anhydride.

A hydroxyflavan with hydroxy groups at positions 3 and 4. Further oxygenation may be present at other ring positions. They are considered as derivatives of anthocyanidin and hence are termed leucoanthocyanidin.
The selenium ion with two positive charges.
A glycosylglucose comprising beta-D-glucose having a D-galactosyl residue at the 4-position.
A hydroxybenzoate having the hydroxy group at the 4-position together with a geranyl group at the 3-position; major species at pH 7.3.
An amino acid containing one or more nitrogen atoms connected through carbon atoms to one or more carboxy groups.
A hydrate that is the monohydrate form of metoclopramide dihydrochloride.
A racemate is an equimolar mixture of a pair of enantiomers.
A sulfated glycosaminoglycan, a linear polymer that consists of the repeating disaccharide  [3)-beta-Gal-(1->4)-beta-GlcNAc-(1->] and containing sulfo groups located at random positions.
Any  amino sugar that is a monosaccharide in which one alcoholic hydroxy group is replaced by an amino group.
A xylan composed of a beta-(1->4)-linked D-xylose backbone substituted with glucuronic acid residues.
A D-mannoside of D-glyceric acid.
A derivative of the amino acid cysteine formed by the covalent addition of a prenyl residue.
A phospholipid that contains one or more amino groups.
A gluconate that contains a ketonic carbonyl group.
A glucoside in which the anomeric carbon of the glycosidic bond is in an alpha configuration
A glucoside in which the anomeric carbon of the glycosidic bond is in a beta configuration
A methyl glycoside in which the H of the OH group on C-1 of galactose is replaced by a methyl group.
An alkanesulfonic acid obtained by the formal substitution of one of the methyl hydrogens of (2S)-propane-1,2-diol by a sulfonic acid group.
An L-tyrosine derivative having a 3'-O-{[(6-aminohexyl)oxy](hydroxy)phosphoryl}uridine phosphate attached to the phenolic hydroxy group via a phosphoester linkage.
A nitrogen-containing fatty acid anion arising from deprotonation of the carboxy group of any amino fatty acid.
A fatty acid anion arising from deprotonation of the carboxylic acid group of any nitrogen-containing fatty acid.
A  ribonucleoside bisphosphate having uracil as the nucleobase.
A methyl glycoside comprising methyl beta-D-glucoside having an beta-D-galactosyl residue at the 4-position.

Kanamycin is a naturally occurring antibiotic complex from Streptomyces kanamyceticus that consists of several components: kanamycin A, the major component (also usually designated as kanamycin), and kanamycins B, C, D and X the minor components.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the 1- and 2-acyl groups are specified as hexadecanoyl and 9-oxononanoyl respectively.
A hydrate that is the monohydrate form of tacrolimus.
A nucleoside bisphosphate that has a purine nucleobase.
A nucleoside bisphosphate where sugar of the nucleoside is ribose.
A peptidoglycan with a phosphate linkage to a lipid.
A laminarabiose having beta-configuration at the reducing end anomeric centre.
Any compound that has a nucleobase as a part.
